                    properties of linearity, unbiasedness, zero mean value of the random term and minimum variance. The
                    research examined the relationship between independent variables loan provisioning, amount of bad
                    loan, interest rate differentials and the dependent variable, performance which was measured using
                    (return on asset). The choice of these variables is because they all exist in literatures. The study
                    found
                    that the coefficient of volume of loan provisioning is 0.006778, implies that a unit increase in VLP
                    will
                    lead to a proportionate increase in ROA by 0.006778 units. The implication of the coefficient of
                    amount
                    of bad loan (ABL) which is 0.011321 means a unit increase in ABL will consequently increase ROA by
                    the
                    same unit. Same can be said of Interest rate differentials (IRD), a unit increase in IRD will
                    increase ROA
                    by 0.001736 unit. Lastly, holding other variables constant will lead to an increase in ROA by
                    0.523273
                    units. The study concludes that volume of loan provisioning have a positive and insignificant impact
                    on
                    return on asset. The high volume of loan provisioning of banks will have a cushion effect in-case
                    there is
                    any eventuality of bad loans. Finally, interest rate differentials have a positive insignificant
                    impact on
                    return on asset. This implies that interest rate differentials are a weak factor in explaining the
                    variations
                    in the performance of banks, hence the need to have favourable interest rate that is customer
                    friendly.</article>
