            <details>
                <summary>Abstract</summary>
                <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> Nigeria as a nation needs a huge capital to liberate her
                    citizens from the shackle of poverty; with the
                    huge sum of international remittances inflow to Nigeria annually, the question still remain whether
                    remittances inflow have reduced poverty rate as defined by Copenhagen’s Summit of 1995. Therefore,
                    this study examined the effect of remittances inflow on poverty reduction using a time period of
                    1981-
                    2016. The study employed Augmented Dickey Fuller (ADF) and Phillip Peron (PP) unit root test,
                    Johansen
                    Co-integration and Auto-regressive distributed lagged (ARDL). Both the Augmented Dickey Fuller (ADF)
                    and Phillip Peron (PP) unit root test showed that poverty rate and trade openess were stationary at
                    level
                    I(0); while, international remittance inflow, real gross domestic product and exchange rate were
                    stationary at first level difference I(1) using 5% significance level. The Johansen Co-integration
                    established one co-integrating vector; while, the ARDL result showed a negative and significant
                    effect of
                    international remittance inflow on poverty rate. The same finding was established for exchange rate
                    and
                    trade openess. Also the F-statistic of Wald Test was less than the critical upper bound value at 5%.
                    This
                    study therefore, concluded that international remittance inflow is a tentative relief for poverty
                    reduction
                    in Nigeria. The study recommended that house-hold should investment remittances received into more
                    productive businesses.</article>
            </details>
