                <summary>Abstract</summary>
                <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> The study test the influence of liquidity loss on financial
                    returns of listed deposit money banks
                    in nigeria. Practical issues as regard the management of liquidity by deposit money banks were
                    identified ranging from poor working capital ratio in the face of the rampaging inflation rate
                    where the study aimed at assessing the impact of the respective liquidity risk variables used in
                    the study on financial performance. The study sourced data majorly through published annual
                    statement of the evaluated firms for the period 2010-2016. Panel regression analysis was
                    conducted after robustness test. Findings revealed that quick ratio and inflation negatively
                    affect financial performance while current ratio positively but insignificantly affects financial
                    performance. In general, the study concludes that liquidity weakly account for the changes in
                    financial performance by about 25.81%, and proposed that management should pay keen
                    attention to their liquidity level through routine checks by ensuring that it doesn’t fall below the
                    optimal region of 2:1 to retain its market shares. These results contributed to the accounting
                    and finance literature by providing evidence that supports the role played by bank management
                    in cushioning the outcome of liquidty loss on banks financial performance in Nigeria.</article>
